        "excerpt": "O Lord, my heart is not proud, nor my eyes haughty; Nor do I involve myself in great matters, Or in things too difficult for me.",
        "body": "Verse 1 is a confession of what David has *not* done, making it unusual even among psalms of testimony. Most biblical praise reports what God has done; this verse reports what the psalmist has refused to do. The three renunciations form an interior-to-exterior-to-behavioral sequence. **The heart not proud** — *lev* is the Hebrew anthropological center; the command center of desire, will, and self-assessment. Pride (*gavah*) inflates the lev beyond its proper station. **The eyes not haughty** — *ayin* with *rum* (high, elevated) describes the look that expresses and reinforces interior pride. Proverbs 6:16-17 lists 'haughty eyes' first among the seven things the LORD hates; they are the outward signal of the pride-inflated heart. **Not involving oneself in great matters or things too wonderful** — the behavioral consequence of a humble heart. *Gadol* (great) and *pala* (wonderful, surpassing) together describe two categories of overreach: ambition that grasps at a greatness not yet given, and theological presumption that insists on divine explanations God has withheld.\n\nThe verse has a specific historical weight when attributed to David. This is the man anointed king, who slew Goliath, defeated armies, was promised an eternal throne, and wrote much of Israel's sacred poetry. His renunciation of pride is not the claim of someone with nothing to be proud of. Calvin observed that the most dangerous pride is spiritual pride — the pride of the gifted, the chosen, the anointed — because it wears the costume of faithfulness. David renounces exactly that. He does not claim to have earned the right to a humble heart; he claims only to have one.\n\nThe phrase 'things too difficult / too wonderful for me' (*niplao'ot mimmeni*) returns the reader to Job 42:3, where Job confesses, 'I have declared that which I did not understand, things too wonderful for me, which I did not know.' The *pala*-root describes what lies beyond human comprehension — the hidden counsels of God, the dark providences, the unanswered theodicy questions. Psalm 131:1 does not say David has no questions. It says he has stopped *occupying himself with* what he cannot answer. There is a spiritual maturity in knowing that some questions belong to God and not to us — and that ceasing to demand an answer is not defeat but wisdom.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Gavah* (proud) and *rum* (haughty) are near-synonyms for elevation/inflation; together they form a merism covering the full range of pride — interior disposition and exterior display. *Pala* (wonderful, too difficult) — the nipl'al passive of the same root as *niplao'ot*, suggesting the matters are intrinsically beyond human measure, not merely beyond David's current capacity. *Halakh* (aspire, walk toward) in the BSB rendering 'do not aspire to' — *lo' halakhti* — I have not walked in those directions."
