        "title": "The weaned child — the image of achieved interior rest",
        "range": "131:2",
        "excerpt": "Surely I have composed and quieted my soul; Like a weaned child rests against his mother, My soul is like a weaned child within me.",
        "body": "Verse 2 is the psalm's pastoral and theological center. It moves from what David has refused (v.1) to what he has achieved (v.2) — and the achievement is not mere absence of pride but the positive presence of a specific kind of rest. Two verbs describe the action David has taken: **'I have composed'** (*shiviti*, from *shavah* — to level, equalize, make smooth; the same root as Psalm 16:8 'I have set the LORD continually before me') and **'I have quieted'** (*damam* — to be still, silent, to cease from striving; Psalm 62:1). Both are perfect tense — completed. The soul has already been brought to this place. David is not describing an aspiration but reporting an accomplished interior state.\n\nThe image chosen to describe this state is the psalm's most striking feature: a weaned child (*gamal*) resting against its mother. The precision of the image matters enormously. The nursing infant and the weaned child are both attached to the mother, but their attachment is qualitatively different. The nursing infant comes to the breast in need — the relationship is fundamentally extractive: give me what I need or I will cry. The weaned child rests against the mother not because it must extract something but because the mother *is* its home. The relationship has been purified of transaction. The child is not there to get; it is there to be. This is the transformation David claims for his *nephesh* — his soul, the seat of all desire and appetite.\n\nThe word *gamal* is doubled in verse 2, a deliberate literary repetition: 'like a weaned child rests against his mother, my soul is like a weaned child within me.' The repetition is not padding; it is emphasis. The image is laid on twice because it is the psalm's whole point. Derek Kidner (Psalms 73-150, Tyndale OT Commentaries) noted that the weaned child image is disarming precisely because it is not heroic — it is not David the warrior or David the poet but David the child at rest. The psalm's final authority comes from its vulnerability.\n\nThe phrase 'within me' (*alai* — literally 'upon me,' against me) at the end of the verse picks up the same spatial language as the child resting *against* the mother. David's quieted soul is not projected outward into a managed environment; it is resting *against* himself — an interior posture, not an external achievement. The soul has found its resting place in God regardless of what the outside world is doing.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shavah* (composed, leveled) — the same root as Psalm 16:8, where David levels or sets the LORD before him continually; the suggestion is of bringing the soul to a level, balanced state. *Damam* (quieted, stilled) — to cease from striving; the same root in Lamentations 3:26 ('it is good that he waits silently for the salvation of the LORD'). *Gamal* (weaned child) — from the root to ripen or bring to completion; the weaned child is one who has been brought through a maturation process."
